Basically, specifying the min/max will force the labels to appear even without any series that contain data.

Numeric example:

    xAxis: {
      labels: {
    	enabled: true 	
      },
      min: 0,
      max: 100,
      tickWidth: 0,
      tickInterval: 10
    },

Categorical example:

    xAxis: {
    	labels: {
    			enabled: true 	
      },
      categories: [&#39;apples&#39;, &#39;bananas&#39;],
      min: 0,
      max: 1, // = number of categories - 1
    },

There are a couple of solutions to this issue: &lt;br&gt;

1) Set `xAxis.labels.reserveSpace = false`

**Demo:** 

 - http://jsfiddle.net/BlackLabel/1rch9d3b/

2) Set `chart.spacingBottom`

**Demo:**

 - http://jsfiddle.net/BlackLabel/6zwoL2mf/1/

3) In the `xAxis.labels.formatter` callback instead of null return a span element with `opacity = 0`:

      xAxis: {
        labels: {
          formatter: function() {
            let value = this.value;
            let resultValue = value &gt; 100000 ? value : &#39;&lt;span style=&quot;opacity: 0;&quot;&gt;a&lt;/span&gt;&#39;;
            return resultValue;
          },
          enabled: true
        },
        tickWidth: 0
      }

**Demo:**

 - http://jsfiddle.net/BlackLabel/9m51hvgp/

