answers.body_markdown:
You have misunderstood the `properties` meaning. They are not the properties of a class (in general meaning). You can think about them as function variables. Each React component is transpiled to the function call. `&lt;Component /&gt;` becomes `createElement(Component, props, children)`. Here is `props` are your properties you are looking for.

Props are come from the parent component. To make component rerender by himself, you should use `state`. So your example becomes: 

    class Numbers extends Component {
        state = {num: Math.random()}
    
        changeNumber = () =&gt; {
            this.setState({num: Math.random()});
        }
    
        render() {
            return (
                &lt;button onClick={ this.changeNumber }&gt;{this.state.num}&lt;/button&gt;
            );
        }
    }

If you want to update all child components you should add a state to the parent component.


    class Component extends Component {
        state = {num: Math.random()}
    
        changeNumber = () =&gt; {
            this.setState({num: Math.random()});
        }
    
        render() {
            return (
                &lt;Numbers onClick={ this.changeNumber }&gt;{this.state.num}&lt;/Numbers&gt;
            );
        }
    }
    
    function Numbers (props) {
      return &lt;div onClick={props.onClick}&gt;{props.children}&lt;/div&gt;
    }

