answers.body_markdown:
Define `MultipleAddVehicle` as an abstract method in the parent class, and override it in the child class. This will require you to define the parent class as an abstract class:

```csharp
public abstract class Parent
{
    public abstract void MultipleAddVehicle();

    [TestInitialize]
    public void BaseTestInit()
    {
        // ...
    }

    public void LoginAndSelectAutomationFleet()
    {
        // ...
    }

    public void GenerationTestData()
    {
        //First data that is needed is vehicle management data
        //Add multiple vehicles and add unassigned devices and unassigned drivers
        MultipleAddVehicle();
    }
}

public class Child : Parent
{
    public override void MultipleAddVehicle()
    {
        // ...
    }
}
```

This is just good old fashioned object oriented programming. No magic here.

This is very similar to the [Template Method Pattern](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template_method_pattern).

Child class see all members of parent class, but parent class dont see all members of child class, unless it have access to child class object. If child classs is not a static class, then you must create an instance of child class and put a reference on it into parent class. If all classes are in same namespace, they will be visible to each other.


    public class ParentClass
    {
        .................................
    
    
        public ChildClass childclassinstance;
    
        public void GenerationTestData()
            {
                //First data that is needed is vehicle management data
                //Add multiple vehicles and add unassigned devices and unassigned drivers
                childclassinstance.MultipleAddVehicle();
            }
    }
    
    public class ChildClass : ParentClass
    {
         public void MultipleAddVehicle()
            {
            }
    }

Of course, you need to initialize your childclassinstance object before calling it&#39;s methods. You may do it from parent class by default constructor, if you dont care about this specific object values, and just want to call one void method.

    public ChildClass childclassinstance = new ChildClass();

Or you may initialize it from child class if it is created during testing

    childclassinstance = this;

Or you can make MultipleAddVehicle(); a static method, so you do not need to create object, just call it from class type.

    ChildClass.MultipleAddVehicle();

