If you repeat the &quot;same structure of the original&quot; several times in one result, you do not longer have a well-formed document as you then have several root elements, While that is possible in an XSLT transformation result, it is an unusual result. If you really want that kind of result then all you need to do in the approach from the other thread is to explicitly start processing with

        &lt;xsl:template match=&quot;/&quot;&gt;
            &lt;xsl:apply-templates select=&quot;//employee&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;/xsl:template&gt;

and of course remove the use of `xsl:result-document`, so the whole code would look like 

    &lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; encoding=&quot;UTF-8&quot;?&gt;
    &lt;xsl:stylesheet xmlns:xsl=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/XSL/Transform&quot; version=&quot;2.0&quot;
        xmlns:xs=&quot;http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema&quot;
        exclude-result-prefixes=&quot;#all&quot;&gt;
        
        &lt;xsl:strip-space elements=&quot;*&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;xsl:output indent=&quot;yes&quot;/&gt;
        
        &lt;xsl:template match=&quot;/&quot;&gt;
            &lt;xsl:apply-templates select=&quot;//employee&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;/xsl:template&gt;
    
        &lt;xsl:template match=&quot;employee&quot;&gt;
            &lt;xsl:apply-templates select=&quot;/&quot; mode=&quot;split&quot;&gt;
                &lt;xsl:with-param name=&quot;this-split-element&quot; select=&quot;.&quot; tunnel=&quot;yes&quot;/&gt;
